===Etymology 1===
{{etymid|ja|kasa}}
{{ja-kanjitab|かさ|yomi=kun|alt=傘,暈:uncommon,仐:rare}}
[[File:Umbrella_opened.svg|thumb|250px|{{m|ja|傘|id=kasa|tr=kasa}}: an '''umbrella'''.]]
[[File:Rain or Shine 2009 (3887138862).jpg|thumb|250px|{{m|ja|笠|tr=kasa}}: a '''traditional Japanese rain hat'''.]]
[[File:Halo,_observed_in_Tokyo_in_2018.jpg|thumb|250px|{{m|ja|暈|tr=kasa}}: a '''halo''' around the sun.]]
{{swp|ja:}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=かさ|-}}.  Attested in a gloss of the ''{{w|Nihon Shoki}}'' (720) and ''{{w|Man'yōshū}}'' (759) in the ideographic spelling {{m|ja|笠}}.<ref name="NKD2P"/> In turn, from reconstructed {{inh|ja|jpx-pro|sort=かさ|*kasa|t=rain hat}}. Possibly related to {{m|ja|重なる|tr=kasanaru||to overlap, to be layered|pos=intransitive}}, {{m|ja|重ねる|tr=kasaneru||to overlap, to layer|pos=transitive}},<ref name="NKD2P"/>.

The term originally refers to a bundle of reeds or sedges used as a rain hat.<ref name="NKD2P"/>  Following the spread of folding umbrellas in the 900s after their introduction from [[Baekje]] or China, the sense gradually shifted to also mean "{{m|en|umbrella}}".

